TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Tangled Tale of Training and Talent: PhDs in Institutional Asset Management
AU  - Chaudhuri, Ranadeb
AU  - Ivković, Zoran
AU  - Pollet, Joshua
AU  - Trzcinka, Charles
Y1  - 2020/04/10
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2020/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3431
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2019.3431
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 5623
EP  - 5647
VL  - 66
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Performance of investment products managed by firms in which PhDs play a key role is superior to the performance of products managed by otherwise similar firms. This relation is not a result of endogenous matching between firms and PhDs. Performance is related to training (the field of study) because economics or finance PhDs outperform other PhDs. Performance is also related to talent because PhDs who published in top outlets outperform other PhDs. Field-specific training is not relevant among the most talented PhDs because the performance gap between economics or finance PhDs and other PhDs disappears among published PhDs.This paper was accepted by Tyler Shumway, finance.
AB  - Performance of investment products managed by firms in which PhDs play a key role is superior to the performance of products managed by otherwise similar firms. This relation is not a result of endogenous matching between firms and PhDs. Performance is related to training (the field of study) because economics or finance PhDs outperform other PhDs. Performance is also related to talent because PhDs who published in top outlets outperform other PhDs. Field-specific training is not relevant among the most talented PhDs because the performance gap between economics or finance PhDs and other PhDs disappears among published PhDs.This paper was accepted by Tyler Shumway, finance.
